{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f90a4572-c064-4e5f-ba77-996771de83eb","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. You can find it in:\n\n1. **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — per-user crash reports\n2. **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — system-wide crash reports\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_<date>_<machine>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them in a GUI.\n\n**To get a core dump** instead, run before launching your app:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nCore files land in `/cores/core.<pid>` (requires SIP adjustments on modern macOS).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f8914c8b-c41e-46a9-89db-d623079dfbec","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":242},"id":"617b7ddd-4ff9-4e14-8b24-efaebe5c1e2f","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:59:35.626Z","parentId":"37d5eaac-716f-4f02-a664-ed0e06b5490b"}
